<!-- Yishuren -->
<div class="container">
  <h1><span class="heading">WEN·MO</span> 文·墨</h1>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      For new Chinese speakers seeking native materials to engage with, the
      volume of media available can make difficult the process of finding works
      that suit their interests and taste. This is exacerbated by the fact that
      original works that grapple with their creators' environment often fall
      foul of censors, or are deterred from being created in the first place.
    </p>
    <p>
      The effort to engage is worthwhile. There are a wealth of contemporary
      artists and thinkers who convey deep human and social insights with
      dignity, humour, compassion and sorrow. In the case of those whose form of
      self-expression is hazardous, their willingness to continue regardless
      makes their voices especially deserving of an audience.
    </p>
    <p>
      The novelists, essayists, and filmmakers introduced below came via
      friends, other language learners, or chance encounters over years of
      searching. There are many more worth spending time with.
    </p>
