<!-- China Heritage -->
<div class="container" id="China Heritage">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">China Heritage</span></h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      The
      <a href="https://chinaheritage.net/" target="_blank">China Heritage</a>
      project, which also houses The Wairarapa Academy for New Sinology
      清漪書院, is a product of collaboration between sinologist Geremie Barmé
      and fellow scholars of China's culture and politics. In its own words:
    </p>
    <figure class="text">
      <blockquote class="blockquote fs-6 text">
        <p>
          <em>
            China Heritage advocates a New Sinology 後漢學. This is an approach
            to the Chinese and Sinophone world that builds on traditional
            Sinological strengths while emphasising a learned engagement with
            the complex and shifting realities of contemporary China, and the
            Chinese commonwealth (Hong Kong, Taiwan, the People’s Republic and
            the global Sinosphere).
          </em>
        </p>
      </blockquote>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The site is an excellent resource for those interested in extensive
      analysis of contemporary China's politics and society.
    </p>
    <p>
      Its publications provide deep insight into the context of current
      developments, and their coverage of the writings of prominent
      intellectuals - such as the ongoing Xu Zhangrun 許章潤 series - shares
      invaluable expertise on the subtleties of language and historical
      references used to express political opposition, among other insights.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- China Heritage -->
</div>
<!-- Hao Jingfang -->
<div class="container" id="Hao Jingfang">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Hao Jingfang</span> 郝景芳</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Hao Jingfang 郝景芳 (1984 - ) is a science fiction writer and 2016
      recipient of the Hugo Award for Best Novelette.
    </p>
    <p>
      Her novella
      <a
        href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160822161228/http://jessica-hjf.blog.163.com/blog/static/278128102015240444791/"
        target="_blank"
        >Folding Beijing</a
      >
      北京摺曡 is a futuristic riff on the experiences of the city's
      <em>beipiao</em> 北漂 or migrant workers, whose labour is essential to its
      function, and yet must eke out precarious lives in a legal grey zone
      without basic rights.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Hao Jingfang -->
</div>
<!-- Kou Aizhe -->
<div class="container" id="Kou Aizhe">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Kou Aizhe</span> 寇愛哲</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Kou Aizhe 寇愛哲 (1983 - ) is a journalist and the founder of StoryFM
      故事FM, a podcast series that relays personal narratives from ordinary
      people in their own words. With its 700th episode released in early 2023,
      it is an incredible resource that provides a platform for voices across
      the spectrum of human experience.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Kou Aizhe -->
</div>
<!-- Leap -->
<div class="container" id="LEAP">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">LEAP</span> 藝術界</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      LEAP 藝術界 is a biannual, bilingual contemporary art magazine. The print
      edition places the Chinese and English articles versions right beside each
      other, which can be especially useful as a learning tool for gleaning
      context from complex prose. The
      <a href="http://leapleapleap.com/" target="_blank">LEAP website</a>
      provides free access to many of their articles.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Leap -->
</div>
<!-- Li Yu -->
<div class="container" id="Li Yu">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Li Yu</span> 李玉</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>Li Yu 李玉 (1973 - ) is a director and screenwriter.</p>
    <p>
      Her 2007 film Lost in Beijing 蘋果 follows a young couple living as
      migrant workers in Beijing, and deals with strong themes of sexual
      exploitation and gender inequality. The film was heavily censored in China
      despite its entry into the Berlin Film Festival. Its message remains
      pertinent today, as recent high-profile sexual harassment cases and
      crackdowns on feminist movements make clear.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Li Yu -->
</div>
<!-- Liu Cixin -->
<div class="container" id="Liu Cixin">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Liu Cixin</span> 劉慈欣</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Liu Cixin 劉慈欣 (1963 - ) is a science fiction writer, former engineer,
      and recipient of the 2015 Hugo Award for Three Body Problem 三體, the
      first book of his trilogy by the same name.
    </p>
    <p>
      His engineering background shows in the descriptions of a near-future
      Earth trying desperately to develop technological solutions to an
      existential threat, and his exploration of game theory applied to space
      exploration in the second instalment, Dark Forest 黑暗森林, is engaging.
    </p>
    <p>
      The narrative is let down by two-dimensional characters, which rely on
      lazy stereotypes and make some sections tedious, but Liu's strategic plot
      developments and talent for the science he knows is worthwhile for those
      interested in the genre.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Liu Cixin -->
</div>
<!-- Liu Jian -->
<div class="container" id="Liu Jian">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Liu Jian</span> 劉健</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Liu Jian 劉健 (1969 - ) is an animated film director and screenwriter.
    </p>
    <p>
      Dark comedy Have a Nice Day 大世界 follows a series of crimes, set off
      when Xiao Zhang 小張 steals cash from his boss, to fix his girlfriend's
      cosmetic surgery. The dialogue is sublime and brilliantly captures the
      mood of everyday interactions, even while punctuated with Tarantino-style
      violence.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Liu Jian -->
</div>
<!-- Qi Jun -->
<div class="container" id="Qi Jun">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Qi Jun</span> 琦君</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Qi Jun 琦君 (1917 - 2006) was a writer, essayist, critic and translator.
    </p>
    <p>
      Her novel Ripe Tangerine 橘子紅了 is a critique of female exploitation
      under traditional family structures. Xiufen 秀芬 becomes the third wife in
      a rural household, arranged as Dama's 大媽 futile attempt to coax her
      husband back from the city he has abandoned her for to be with his second
      wife.
    </p>
    <p>
      Zhang Yimou 張藝謀 explored similar themes in his film Raise the Red
      Lantern 大紅燈籠高高挂， released the same year in 1991.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Qi Jun -->
</div>
<!-- Qian Zhongshu -->
<div class="container" id="Qian Zhongshu">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Qian Zhongshu</span> 錢鍾書</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Qian Zhongshu 錢鍾書 (1910 - 1998) was a scholar and writer, and one of
      the most lauded Chinese literary figures of the 20th century.
    </p>
    <p>
      Fortress Beseiged 圍城 is a satirical novel written during his time in
      Shanghai under Japanese occupation. Centred on Fang Hongjian 方鴻漸, who
      has returned home after squandering funds and his studies in Europe, the
      book takes on middle-class affectations and relationships during the
      Republic of China era.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Qian Zhongshu -->
</div>
<!-- Sanmao -->
<div class="container" id="San Mao">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Sanmao</span> 三毛</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Sanmao 三毛 was the pseudonym of Echo Chen Ping 陳平 (1943 - 1991), a
      writer and translator. Her then-unconventional lifestyle, which saw her
      leave Taiwan alone for Europe and Morocco, embodied a free and independent
      way of life that inspired many across the Chinese-speaking world.
    </p>
    <p>
      Stories of the Sahara 撒哈拉的故事 is typical of her autobiographical
      writing style, based on her experiences living in Morocco with her Spanish
      husband, who passed away in an accident just a few years after
      publication. Her struggles to cope with this loss informed much of her
      subsequent work, and likely contributed to her suicide a decade later.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Sanmao -->
</div>
<!-- Wang Shuo -->
<div class="container" id="Wang Shuo">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Wang Shuo</span> 王朔</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Wang Shuo 王朔 (1958 - ) is a novelist and screenwriter. Known for his
      <em>liu mang</em> 流氓 or hooligan style of writing, his works have been
      popular source material for film and television since the late 1980s.
    </p>
    <p>
      The dark humour of Please Don't Call Me Human 千萬別把我當人 gets close to
      the bone with its ridicule of totalitarian bureaucracy. Published in the
      1980s, a similar work could not evade censorship today.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Wang Shuo -->
</div>
<!-- Wang Xiaobo -->
<div class="container" id="Wang Xiaobo">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Wang Xiaobo</span> 王小波</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Wang Xiaobo 王小波 (1952 - 1997) was a novelist and essayist. Born in
      Beijing, he was amongst the many 'sent-down' or 'educated' youths 知識青年
      extracted from urban life to labour in rural areas during the Cultural
      Revolution 文革.
    </p>
    <p>
      That experience influenced some of his best-known works, including the
      satirical Golden Age 黃金時代. Essay collections such as Silent Majority
      沉默的大多數 exhibit his vernacular wit and talent for querying social
      norms.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Wang Xiaobo -->
</div>
<!-- Wang Xiaoshuai -->
<div class="container" id="Wang Xiaoshuai">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Wang Xiaoshuai</span> 王小帥</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Wang Xiaoshuai 王小帥 (1966 - ) is a director and screenwriter, regarded
      as a member of China's "sixth wave" of independent filmmakers.
    </p>
    <p>
      Set in Beijing, Red Amnesia 闖入者 is a psychological thriller, centred on
      an elderly woman disturbed by flashbacks linked to her actions during the
      Cultural Revolution. The film raises questions about the persistent trauma
      of that era, a subject that remains cut off from open discourse.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Wang Xiaoshuai -->
</div>
<!-- Wu Ming-Yi -->
<div class="container" id="Wu Ming-Yi">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Wu Ming-Yi</span> 吳明益</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Wu Ming-Yi 吳明益 (1971 - ) is a writer, artist and academic, and a
      professor of Chinese literature at National Dong Hwa University
      國立東華大學. His writing has explored environmentalism and themes unique
      to Taiwan, such as the influence of the island's Japanese occupation.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Stolen Bicycle 單車失竊記 revolves around a man seeking his
      long-absent father, with meditations on Taiwan's role in World War II. His
      meticulous effort to piece together whatever fragments he can - down to
      cataloguing bicycles used in the theatre his father served in - vividly
      contrasts the inability to know the person at the centre of his search.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
  <!-- Wu Ming-Yi -->
</div>
<!-- Xie Zifan -->
<div class="container" id="Xie Zifan">
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-center">
    <div>
      <h3><span class="heading">Xie Zifan</span> 謝子凡</h3>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container-fluid col-md-8 text-start mt-3">
    <p>
      Xie Zifan 謝子凡 (19?? - ) is an author, translator, and former
      advertiser.
    </p>
    <p>
      Me and the Garbage Truck I Chased 我和我追逐的垃圾車 is a collection of
      semi-autobiographical short stories. Divided across four themes (Hot -
      Cold - Dark - Light), Xie's restrained but reflective writing style gives
      depth to her everyday subject matter.
    </p>
    <!-- Dividing line -->
    <hr class="hr my-4" />
  </div>
